---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Container from "../components/ui/Container.astro";
import SectionHeading from "../components/ui/SectionHeading.astro";
import { asset } from "../lib/asset";

const sections = [
  { id: "conviction", label: "I. The conviction" },
  { id: "test", label: "II. The test" },
  { id: "practice", label: "III. The practice" },
  { id: "further-reading", label: "Further reading" },
];

const niv = (ref: string) =>
  `https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=${encodeURIComponent(ref)}&version=NIV`;

const refClass =
  "underline decoration-ink/25 decoration-1 underline-offset-2 hover:decoration-red-500 hover:text-red-500";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Songwriting & Song Selection Manifesto"
  description="The convictions, scriptures, and standards Public Worship holds our songwriting and song selection to."
>
  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <Container size="default">
      <SectionHeading eyebrow="Manifesto" align="left" as="h1">
        Songwriting & <span class="text-red-500">Song Selection</span> Manifesto
      </SectionHeading>
    </Container>
  </section>

  <section class="pb-8">
    <Container size="default">
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-cream-soft border border-ink/15 p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="font-display text-xl sm:text-2xl font-normal text-ink leading-snug">
          We center our catalog on <span class="text-red-500">throne-room worship</span> — songs whose
          primary content is who God is, with the worshiper present only in
          ways that magnify Him.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-sm sm:text-base text-ink/85 leading-relaxed">
          This is a curatorial focus, not a verdict on other forms of worship
          music. Scripture models many registers — lament, testimony,
          confession, petition — and we honor them. We are choosing to
          specialize in what we believe is most lacking in contemporary
          worship: songs that simply declare God Himself, sustained from the
          first line to the last.
        </p>
      </div>
    </Container>
  </section>

  <section class="pb-8">
    <Container size="default">
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-pink-softer/40 border border-pink-soft/60 p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="font-display text-lg font-normal text-ink">In this document</p>
        <ol class="mt-4 grid gap-x-8 gap-y-1.5 sm:grid-cols-2 list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-ink/85">
          {sections.map((s) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="text-ink hover:text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                {s.label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ol>
      </div>
    </Container>
  </section>

  <section class="pb-24">
    <Container size="default">
      <div class="max-w-prose pw-prose text-ink/85 leading-relaxed">

        <article id="conviction" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-12 first:mt-0">
          <h2 class="font-display font-normal text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-ink">I. The conviction</h2>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-4">
            <p>
              The Hebrew word most often translated <em>worship</em> is
              <strong class="font-semibold">shâchâh</strong> — to bow down.
              In <a href={niv("John 4:23-24")} class={refClass}>John 4</a>
              Jesus says the Father seeks worshipers who worship in spirit
              and in truth. In <a href={niv("Psalm 29")} class={refClass}>Psalm 29</a>
              we are told to <em>ascribe to the LORD the glory due his name</em>.
              Two anchors that hold this whole document together.
            </p>
            <p>
              Our specific focus is
              <strong class="font-semibold">throne-room worship</strong>.
              The image is John's vision in Revelation:
            </p>
            <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-ink/20 pl-4 italic text-ink/80">
              "Holy, holy, holy is the Lord God Almighty, who was, and is,
              and is to come." (<a href={niv("Revelation 4:8")} class={refClass}>Rev 4:8</a>)
              <br /><br />
              "Worthy is the Lamb, who was slain." (<a href={niv("Revelation 5:12")} class={refClass}>Rev 5:12</a>)
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              The worshipers are present. They are not the subject. The
              Lamb is. This is the shape we want to multiply — and the
              shape that, when we look honestly at contemporary worship, we
              believe is rarest.
            </p>
            <p>
              We are not saying other forms of worship music are wrong.
              Scripture models many registers, and we sing songs in all of
              them when the moment calls for them. We are saying this: the
              church already has lament, testimony, and confession in
              abundance. The kind of song that simply declares God —
              sustained, with the worshiper present only to bow lower — is
              what we are choosing to make more of.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article id="test" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-16">
          <h2 class="font-display font-normal text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-ink">II. The test</h2>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-4">
            <p>
              For any lyric — one we have written or are considering
              leading — we ask:
              <strong class="font-semibold">what is the function of the
              worshiper's presence?</strong> And:
              <strong class="font-semibold">is she giving something to God,
              or reporting something about herself?</strong> The pronoun
              does not decide it. The function does.
            </p>

            <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-2 sm:mx-0 mt-4">
              <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
                <thead>
                  <tr class="text-left border-b border-ink/20">
                    <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-display font-normal text-ink">Function of self in the lyric</th>
                    <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-display font-normal text-ink">Example</th>
                    <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-display font-normal text-ink whitespace-nowrap">Verdict</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-ink/10">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self absent, <em>or</em> "we" / "the saints" / "all creation" present only as those who bow, ascribe, or fall down (<strong class="font-semibold">ascription</strong>)</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"A thousand generations falling down in worship"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-red-500 whitespace-nowrap">✓ Welcome</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self <em>giving</em> attention / wonder / voice / awe outward to God (<strong class="font-semibold">offering</strong>)</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"When I in awesome wonder consider all the works thy hands have made"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-red-500 whitespace-nowrap">✓ Welcome</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self present only to be made small / brought low (<strong class="font-semibold">diminishment</strong>)</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"If the highest place I reach is at Your feet"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-red-500 whitespace-nowrap">✓ Welcome</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self present only to be yielded to God's authority (<strong class="font-semibold">surrender</strong>)</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"Take my life and let it be consecrated, Lord, to Thee"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-red-500 whitespace-nowrap">✓ Welcome</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self as the discoverer / surprised / one whose realization is the song's content</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"Who thought I'd find You at the lowest place?"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-ink/60 whitespace-nowrap">✗ Not the diet</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self as the recipient of affection / identity / security</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"I'll never be more loved than I am right now"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-ink/60 whitespace-nowrap">✗ Not the diet</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self as the testifier recounting what God did <em>for me</em></td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"He makes me lie down in green pastures"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-ink/60 whitespace-nowrap">✗ Not the diet</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top">Self as the resolved / committer / one who promises</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top italic text-ink/75">"I'll never let go of Your hand"</td>
                    <td class="py-2 pr-3 align-top text-ink/60 whitespace-nowrap">✗ Not the diet</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-3 text-xs sm:text-sm text-ink/60">
              The welcome zone has four shapes —
              <em>self appears only to make God greater, or not at all</em>.
              The not-the-diet zone has four —
              <em>self carries the song</em>.
            </p>

            <aside class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-pink-softer/30 border border-pink-soft/50 p-5">
              <p class="font-display text-base text-ink">"We" vs "I"</p>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink/85 leading-relaxed">
                The test is grammatical-person-blind. Swapping "I" for "we"
                does not move a song from one zone to the other.
                <em>"We'll never be more loved than we are right now"</em>
                is still self-as-recipient-of-affection — just collective.
                Read for function, not for pronoun.
              </p>
            </aside>

            <aside class="mt-3 rounded-xl bg-pink-softer/30 border border-pink-soft/50 p-5">
              <p class="font-display text-base text-ink">Giving vs reporting</p>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink/85 leading-relaxed">
                The same verb does completely different work depending on
                direction. <em>"When I in awesome wonder consider all the
                works thy hands have made"</em> uses "I" as the giver of
                consideration outward to God's works — offering, and welcome.
                <em>"Who thought I'd find You at the lowest place?"</em>
                uses "I" as the reporter of personal surprise — testimony,
                and not the diet. Both lines have "I" as grammatical
                subject; the function is opposite.
              </p>
            </aside>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-8">The four welcome shapes</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Ascription.</strong> Direct
                declaration of who God is and what He has done.
                <em>
                  <a href={niv("Isaiah 6:3")} class={refClass}>Isa 6:3</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Revelation 4:8")} class={refClass}>Rev 4:8</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Revelation 5:12")} class={refClass}>5:12</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Psalm 99")} class={refClass}>Ps 99</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Philippians 2:6-11")} class={refClass}>Phil 2:6–11</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Colossians 1:15-20")} class={refClass}>Col 1:15–20</a>.
                </em>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Offering / praise-giving.</strong>
                Self as the giver of attention, wonder, voice, awe —
                faculties turned Godward as the medium of praise. Includes
                the worshiper's act of giving thanks outward to God.
                <em>
                  <a href={niv("Psalm 34:3")} class={refClass}>Ps 34:3</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Psalm 103:1")} class={refClass}>103:1</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Psalm 121:1")} class={refClass}>121:1</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Psalm 145:1-2")} class={refClass}>145:1–2</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Luke 1:46")} class={refClass}>Lk 1:46</a>.
                </em>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Diminishment.</strong> Self
                appears only to be made small under God.
                <em>
                  <a href={niv("Job 40:4")} class={refClass}>Job 40:4</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Isaiah 6:5")} class={refClass}>Isa 6:5</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Luke 5:8")} class={refClass}>Lk 5:8</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Genesis 18:27")} class={refClass}>Gen 18:27</a>;
                  <a href={niv("John 3:30")} class={refClass}>Jn 3:30</a>.
                </em>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Surrender.</strong> Self
                appears only to be yielded to God's authority.
                <em>
                  <a href={niv("Romans 12:1")} class={refClass}>Rom 12:1</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Luke 22:42")} class={refClass}>Lk 22:42</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Luke 1:38")} class={refClass}>Lk 1:38</a>;
                  <a href={niv("Isaiah 6:8")} class={refClass}>Isa 6:8</a>.
                </em>
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">A note on "blessed be God" and thanksgiving forms</p>
            <p>
              The biblical eulogies (<a href={niv("Ephesians 1:3-14")} class={refClass}>Eph 1:3–14</a>;
              <a href={niv("1 Peter 1:3-5")} class={refClass}>1 Pet 1:3–5</a>;
              <a href={niv("2 Corinthians 1:3-4")} class={refClass}>2 Cor 1:3–4</a>;
              the <a href={niv("Luke 1:68-79")} class={refClass}>Benedictus</a>)
              and the thanksgiving forms in Paul's letters sit on the
              boundary of our welcome zone. They pass when their focus
              stays on God's character and Christ's acts; they drift when
              they dwell on what we received ("who comforts us in all our
              troubles", "salvation from our enemies"). The form itself is
              biblical. The drift is what we watch for. Apply the test line
              by line.
            </p>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">Acknowledged but not centered</p>
            <p>
              Lament (<a href={niv("Psalm 13")} class={refClass}>Ps 13</a>;
              <a href={niv("Psalm 22")} class={refClass}>22</a>;
              <a href={niv("Psalm 130")} class={refClass}>130</a>),
              testimony (<a href={niv("Psalm 23")} class={refClass}>Ps 23</a>;
              <a href={niv("Psalm 116")} class={refClass}>116</a>;
              the <a href={niv("Luke 1:46-55")} class={refClass}>Magnificat</a>),
              confession (<a href={niv("Psalm 51")} class={refClass}>Ps 51</a>),
              and petition (<a href={niv("Psalm 40")} class={refClass}>Ps 40</a>;
              the <a href={niv("Matthew 6:9-13")} class={refClass}>Lord's Prayer</a>).
              We sing these. We do not build our identity around them,
              because the church already has them in abundance.
            </p>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">A note on mixed songs</p>
            <p>
              Many beloved worship songs and hymns have a strong
              throne-room hook wrapped in testimony-framed verses. They are
              not bad. We will sing some of them. But the shape we are
              trying to write more of is
              <strong class="font-semibold">the song that is throne-room
              throughout</strong> — no testimony scaffolding leading into a
              vertical chorus. Just sustained praise. That shape is rare,
              and that rareness is what we are addressing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article id="practice" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-16">
          <h2 class="font-display font-normal text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-ink">III. The practice</h2>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-4">
            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink">What we're guarding against</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Self as ground.</strong> Songs
                that locate the worshiper's identity, worthiness, or
                victory in the worshiper rather than in Christ.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Self as testifier.</strong>
                Songs structured as personal narrative — what I thought,
                what I discovered, what I will feel — where God is the
                surprise resolution rather than the subject.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Self as resolved.</strong>
                Songs where the energy is the worshiper's commitment or
                grit ("I'll never let go"), and God recedes into the object
                of that resolve.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">Our commitments</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Theological soundness, non-negotiable.</strong>
                Every release is checked against Scripture and our
                <a href={asset("/beliefs")} class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">Statement of Beliefs</a>.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Writers as stewards of the test.</strong>
                Every writing room has someone whose job is to apply the
                test to the lyric before the song leaves the room.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">The same standard for songs we did not write.</strong>
                When we lead a cover, a hymn, or a worship song already in
                circulation, it goes through the same test. Popularity does
                not exempt it.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Singability.</strong> Songs
                are written so a congregation can actually sing them in the
                rooms where we lead worship.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong class="font-semibold">Fear of God in the room.</strong>
                Songwriting that calls itself worship is no small thing. We
                approach the work as people who will give an account.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">An invitation</p>
            <p>
              If you write gospel music, we invite you into the same
              standard. Write the song that is throne-room from the first
              line to the last. Hold yourself to Scripture before you hold
              yourself to the algorithm. We will be glad to hear what you
              write.
            </p>

            <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink mt-6">Closing</p>
            <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-ink/20 pl-4 italic text-ink/80">
              "The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom." (<a href={niv("Proverbs 9:10")} class={refClass}>Proverbs 9:10</a>)
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              We do not begin with method. We begin with bowing. We will
              fail. When we do, we want to be told, with Scripture in hand.
              We are submitting this work to God and to His people.
            </p>
            <p class="text-ink/70">— The Public Worship Team</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article id="further-reading" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-16">
          <h2 class="font-display font-normal text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-ink">Further reading</h2>
          <div class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-4">
            <p>
              Free articles and primary sources online — the ones we have
              found most worth the time.
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3">
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.newadvent.org/fathers/110110.htm" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Augustine of Hippo, <em>Confessions</em> Book X.33
                </a> (c. 400). The fourth-century locus classicus on music
                in worship: "When it happens to me to be more moved by the
                singing than by what is sung, I confess myself to have
                sinned criminally." Short, devastating, still load-bearing.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.ccel.org/ccel/ccel/eee/files/wattsprh.htm" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Isaac Watts, Preface to <em>Hymns and Spiritual Songs</em>
                </a> (1707). The 18th-century defense of writing worship
                in the worshiper's voice. Read it as a check on
                overcorrecting our own position.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://worshipmatters.com/2006/12/01/worship-leaders-pastors-evaluating-worship-song-lyrics/" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Bob Kauflin, "Worship Leaders/Pastors: Evaluating Worship Song Lyrics"
                </a> (2006). A working worship pastor's checklist for
                testing lyrics. Practitioner-grade.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.thegospelcoalition.org/blogs/justin-taylor/dont-neglect-the-horizontal-dimension-of-singing-and-worship/" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Justin Taylor, "Don't Neglect the Horizontal Dimension of Singing and Worship"
                </a> (TGC, 2017). The strongest free counter-voice to our
                framing — tests our position against
                <a href={niv("Ephesians 5:19")} class={refClass}>Eph 5:19</a>
                and <a href={niv("Colossians 3:16")} class={refClass}>Col 3:16</a>.
                Read it before you trust our position too much.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.christianitytoday.com/2021/05/marva-dawn-tribute-worship-christians-equipped-ministry/" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Marva Dawn, tribute and quotes (Christianity Today, 2021)
                </a>. The closest free entry point to her core critique of
                self-focused worship — "too much music being used today is
                narcissistic — it's about us and how we feel about God."
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://three-things.ca/the-costly-loss-of-lament-for-the-church/" class="text-red-500 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                  Walter Brueggemann, "The Costly Loss of Lament" (summary)
                </a>. A faithful summary of Brueggemann's 1986 essay. The
                indispensable counter-voice for any catalog tempted to
                skip lament — a vertical-only worship that excludes "Why
                are you cast down, O my soul?" is, on his account,
                theologically dangerous in the opposite direction.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </Container>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
